{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nR1 (asserted-capability probe), R3 (decomposition-shape), and R4 (necessity gate) all gate on\nDETECTION POWER, which can only be measured against plans whose defects are KNOWN. This story\nbuilds that ground truth by CONSTRUCTION: take real cleanly-closed plans, seed exactly one defect\nper class, and the mutation itself is the label — no fresh LLM adjudication (which would duplicate\nthe gate's own sidecar and be circular; that is why E1's finding-level LLM labeling was\ninvalidated). The unmutated originals are the controls that bound blocking false positives under\nthe Tricorder ~10%-blocking-FP trust cliff.\n\nThis is the falsifiable experiment named verbatim in `docs/research/task-decomposition-sota-2026.md`\n§6 R3 (lines 183): \"Seeded-flaw eval: take 10 real historical epics that closed cleanly; generate\nmutated variants — re-sliced into layer-cake children, and with one ordering edge deleted where\nconsumption exists. Pass condition: ≥7/10 mutants flagged, ≤1/10 originals flagged (i.e., ≥87%\ndiscrimination). This reuses the review machinery's batch runner; mutation is mechanical.\" E2\ngeneralizes that one class to all five defect classes the epic names.\n\n**How E2 feeds the epic's result gates.** E2 produces the labeled-positive corpus + a CURRENT-gate\nbaseline table; it is the reference point the amended-gate R-rows are judged against, NOT itself a\ngate change (no `src/rebar` edit). It is consumed jointly:\n- **R1 (59b7)** result gate — asserted-capability detection (class 1) is judged on E2's class-1\n  mutants TOGETHER WITH E3's counterfactual replay (the two halves of R1's evidence).\n- **R3 (3a27)** result gate — layer-cake + consumed-artifact-ordering detection (classes 2, 3) is\n  judged on E2's class-2/3 mutants TOGETHER WITH E6's judge-reliability (E6 certifies the flag\n  labels E2's discrimination number is computed from).\n- **R4 (03a9)** consumes E2's class-4 (unnecessary-mechanism) mutants; **R2 (b080)** consumes E2's\n  class-5 mutants as a supplementary construct-valid signal (R2's own authoritative gate is a\n  lexicon precision/recall eval, not seeded-mutant detection — see the threshold note in ## What).\n\nPrior art the method rests on: in-repo, `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/harnesses/seedpilot.py`\n+ `runs/seedpilot.jsonl` already pilot the seeded BAD/GOOD-plan pattern per criterion (verdicts\nPASS/AMBIGUOUS/FAIL); external, CodePlan's integration-truth argument (layer-cake) and\nclaude-task-master's lower-ID-only DAG / Kiro's waves (consumption-ordering), cited in §6 R3.\n\n## What\n\nBuild a seeded-defect benchmark from real cleanly-closed plans drawn from the E1 outcome corpus\n(`docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/outcome_corpus.jsonl`, 628 rows, 9-key schema per\n`runs/README.md:53-66`), run the CURRENT plan-review gate over it, and commit the corpus + labels +\npre-registered thresholds + baseline detection/FP table. Five defect classes, each mutated\nmechanically from a real base plan:\n\n1. **absent asserted capability** — plan asserts an existing named module provides a capability it\n   lacks (the E1-verified MISS class: dc58-af7b / db7b-c8fd / 5886-d028).\n2. **layer-cake split** — children re-partitioned by architectural layer (schema/backend/frontend/\n   tests) so no single child yields an end-to-end observable outcome.\n3. **consumed-artifact-without-ordering-edge** — a child's text names an artifact/interface a\n   sibling creates, with NO `depends_on`/`blocks` edge or explicit sequencing.\n4. **unnecessary mechanism** — a change the plan does not need (FixedBench over-action).\n5. **untagged operational AC** — an AC whose completion evidence lives outside the codebase, with\n   the `[operator-attested]` tag stripped.\n\n**\"Cleanly-closed\" is a precise, codebase-grounded filter** (defect class had no def before). A base\nticket qualifies iff its `outcome_corpus.jsonl` row satisfies ALL of:\n`post_claim_edit_class == \"none\" AND reopen_count == 0 AND force_close == False AND\ncompletion_verifier_fail_count == 0 AND had_persisted_review == True`\n(every field is a real corpus key — verified against `runs/README.md:57-66`), AND — because the\ncorpus records no live status or child count — its live status is `closed` (from `rebar show`) AND,\nfor the container-shaped classes 2 & 3, it has ≥2 children (from `rebar list --parent`). This filter\nselects **515 clean tickets, of which 292 are containers (31 epic + 261 story)** — verified by\nrunning the filter over the committed corpus — so ≥10 distinct base plans per class is comfortably\navailable. Bugs are EXCLUDED as base plans (plan-review-exempt: `review_plan` returns PASS\nrunner=exempt for `bug`/`session_log`).\n\n**The CURRENT-gate baseline is the reference point, not a pass claim.** The detectors R1/R3/R4\npropose do not yet exist in the shipped gate, so the current gate is EXPECTED to detect classes 1/4\nweakly (there is no dedicated asserted-capability or necessity criterion today). E2 measures where\nthe current gate stands against each pre-registered target; the R-rows are the stories that close\nthe gap. Detection is attributed by CRITERION FAMILY (the mutant vs. its control differ by exactly\none seeded defect, so a family firing only on the mutant is attributable to the defect), using the\ncurrent gate's nearest existing criteria, each validated against the live registry\n(`plan_review.registry.by_id`) at run time so no non-existent criterion id is asserted:\n\n| Class | Target criterion family (current gate) | Detection tier |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 absent capability | `E4`, `G1G2`, `G6` | agentic |\n| 2 layer-cake | `G3`, `G4` | container |\n| 3 consumed-artifact / ordering | `G4` | container |\n| 4 unnecessary mechanism | `E4`, `A1`, `G6` | agentic |\n| 5 untagged operational AC | `P6` | DET floor |\n\n**Pre-registered per-class thresholds (pinned in E2 itself — there is NO single epic \"gate table\";\nthe epic states thresholds live in child ACs).** Committed to `runs/e2_thresholds.json` BEFORE any\ndetector run. Defaults are the §6 R3 discrimination bar (≥7/10 mutants flagged, ≤1/10 controls\nflagged); classes 1 and 4 are pinned STRICTER to match their child ACs (R1 59b7: ≥80% detection /\n≤10% blocking-FP; R4 03a9: ≥8/10 / ≤1/10):\n\n| Class | detection target (mutants) | blocking-FP bound (controls) | matches |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | ≥8/10 flagged | ≤1/10 blocking-flagged | R1 59b7 (≥80% / ≤10%) |\n| 2 | ≥7/10 flagged | ≤1/10 blocking-flagged | R3 3a27 |\n| 3 | ≥7/10 flagged | ≤1/10 blocking-flagged | R3 3a27 |\n| 4 | ≥8/10 flagged | ≤1/10 blocking-flagged | R4 03a9 |\n| 5 | ≥7/10 flagged | ≤1/10 blocking-flagged | E2 default (R2 b080 gates class 5 by lexicon precision, not seeded-mutant detection — E2's number is a supplementary signal) |\n\n**AMBIGUOUS / INDETERMINATE verdict handling (the counting rule, pinned).** The production gate\nemits verdict `PASS | BLOCK | INDETERMINATE` (`plan_review/__init__.py:408`; §5.1 shows INDETERMINATE\nat 8% of real reviews) and per-finding `decision ∈ {block, advisory, dropped, indeterminate}`. A\npure helper `classify_pair(verdict_dict, target_criteria)` applies:\n- **detected (mutant, recall):** a target-family finding surfaced with `decision ∈ {block,\n  advisory}` — advisory counts, because the proposed criteria ship advisory-first.\n- **blocking-FP (control):** a target-family finding surfaced with `decision == block` on the\n  unmutated original — advisory findings on controls are NOT false positives (advisory-first\n  discipline; the Tricorder cliff is a blocking-FP bound).\n- **INDETERMINATE ⇒ gate did not act:** an INDETERMINATE verdict (or a target-family finding with\n  `decision == indeterminate`) counts as NOT DETECTED (FN) on a mutant and NOT a false positive on a\n  control. Justification: an abstain names no defect, so it cannot be credited as a catch (this is\n  the strict choice — abstains can never inflate recall) and it raises no blocking finding, so it\n  cannot count against precision.\n- **Run-validity guard:** because a degenerate high-abstain run would spuriously read as perfect\n  FP-avoidance, a run is INVALID and must be re-run if >20% of a class's mutants OR >20% of its\n  controls return verdict INDETERMINATE (2.5× the 8% historical base rate). The guard and the raw\n  verdict distribution are recorded so abstains are auditable, not hidden.\n\n**Degradation if a class cannot reach 10 real base plans.** (a) One clean container seeds MULTIPLE\nsame-class mutants (different children re-sliced for class 2; different ordering edges deleted for\nclass 3), so 10 mutants ≠ 10 distinct bases — the primary path to N=10. (b) If a class still cannot\nreach 10 distinct real bases, drop to the available N≥5, keep the thresholds as RATES (≥70%\ndetection, ≤10% blocking-FP), and record the exact shortfall N in the README — never pad with\nnon-clean plans. (c) If a class cannot reach N≥5 real bases (the class-2/3 container-shortage risk),\nsynthesize construct-valid base plans for THAT class only, label them `synthetic_base: true`, and\nreport those numbers separately from the real-base classes so reduced ecological validity is\nvisible. The measured pool (292 clean containers) makes (b)/(c) unlikely, but the ladder is pinned.\n\n## Scope\n\n- `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/harnesses/assemble_e2_mutants.py` — **mutation-assembly\n  script.** Loads the outcome corpus, applies the cleanly-closed filter (+ live `closed` status +\n  ≥2-children check for classes 2/3), pulls each selected ticket's plan text and children via\n  `rebar` reads, applies the per-class mechanical mutation, and writes the mutant corpus with\n  labels + diffs. `--dry-run` prints the selected base pool without writing.\n- `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/harnesses/run_e2_benchmark.py` — **benchmark harness (distinct\n  deliverable).** Materializes each mutant AND its control (plus children) as tickets in an ISOLATED\n  throwaway rebar store (`rebar init` under `tempfile.mkdtemp()`, `REBAR_SYNC_PUSH=off` so nothing\n  touches the shared `.tickets-tracker` branch / origin), runs the CURRENT gate\n  `rebar.llm.plan_review.review_plan(id, repo_root=<tmp-store>, source=\"local\", sign=False,\n  emit_sidecar=False)` (`__init__.py:387`; ticket reads hit the tmp store, code grounding reads the\n  real in-place checkout), applies the counting rule, journals raw verdicts incrementally (crash-\n  resumable), and writes the per-class baseline table. Reads its targets from `runs/e2_thresholds.json`.\n- `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/harnesses/e2_counting.py` — the pure `classify_pair` counting\n  helper (no `anthropic`/LLM import), imported by the harness and by the unit test.\n- `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e2_mutant_corpus.jsonl` — committed corpus (one row per\n  mutant AND per control).\n- `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e2_thresholds.json` — pre-registered per-class thresholds\n  (committed BEFORE the baseline run).\n- `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e2_baseline.json` — per-class detection/FP/indeterminate\n  table; `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e2_verdicts.jsonl` — raw per-row gate output.\n- `docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/README.md` — E2 writeup section (method, pre-registered\n  thresholds, baseline results, per-R-row consumption, run-validity guard, degradation ladder).\n- `tests/unit/experiments/test_e2_counting.py` — CI-collectable golden test for `classify_pair`\n  (synthetic verdict dicts, no LLM).\n- **NO `src/rebar` gate/source changes** (E2 is measurement, not a gate change).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `runs/e2_mutant_corpus.jsonl` holds ≥10 MUTANT rows for each of the 5 defect classes, each\n  paired with exactly one CONTROL row, every row carrying `pair_id`, `defect_class`,\n  `role ∈ {mutant,control}`, `source_ticket_id`, `plan_text`, `children`, and (mutants) a\n  `mutation_op` + `mutation_diff`. Prove:\n  `python3 -c \"import json,collections as c; rows=[json.loads(l) for l in open('docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e2_mutant_corpus.jsonl')]; m=c.Counter(r['defect_class'] for r in rows if r['role']=='mutant'); ctl=c.Counter(r['defect_class'] for r in rows if r['role']=='control'); assert set(m)==set(ctl)=={'1','2','3','4','5'}, m; assert all(m[k]>=10 and m[k]==ctl[k] for k in m), (dict(m),dict(ctl)); print('OK', dict(m))\"`\n- [ ] The cleanly-closed filter is implemented in `assemble_e2_mutants.py` exactly as\n  `post_claim_edit_class==\"none\" AND reopen_count==0 AND force_close==False AND\n  completion_verifier_fail_count==0 AND had_persisted_review==True` (+ live `closed` + ≥2 children\n  for classes 2/3), and every `source_ticket_id` in the corpus satisfies it. Prove (cross-check each\n  base against its corpus row):\n  `python3 docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/harnesses/assemble_e2_mutants.py --dry-run --verify-clean && echo FILTER-OK`\n  (exits 0 only if every selected base ticket's corpus row passes the 5-condition filter; non-zero\n  names the first violating ticket).\n- [ ] `runs/e2_thresholds.json` pins the per-class detection target + blocking-FP bound for all 5\n  classes and the INDETERMINATE run-validity cap, and is committed in a commit that PRECEDES the\n  commit adding `runs/e2_baseline.json`. Prove structure + pre-registration order:\n  `python3 -c \"import json; t=json.load(open('docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e2_thresholds.json')); assert set(t['classes'])=={'1','2','3','4','5'} and all({'detection_min','blocking_fp_max'}<=set(t['classes'][k]) for k in t['classes']) and 'indeterminate_cap' in t; print('THRESHOLDS-OK')\"`\n  and (strict precedence — the thresholds commit must be a DISTINCT, earlier commit than the\n  baseline-run commit):\n  `TH=$(git log --diff-filter=A --format=%H -1 -- docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e2_thresholds.json); BL=$(git log --diff-filter=A --format=%H -1 -- docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e2_baseline.json); [ \"$TH\" != \"$BL\" ] && git merge-base --is-ancestor \"$TH\" \"$BL\" && echo PRE-REGISTERED-OK`\n- [ ] `run_e2_benchmark.py` runs the CURRENT gate (`review_plan`, sign=False, emit_sidecar=False,\n  source=\"local\") over every mutant + control and writes `runs/e2_baseline.json` — a per-class table\n  with `n_mutants, n_controls, detected, detection_rate, blocking_fp, fp_rate, indeterminate_mutants,\n  indeterminate_controls, meets_threshold` — plus raw output to `runs/e2_verdicts.jsonl`. Prove all 5\n  classes present with the required fields and every verdict is in the closed vocabulary:\n  `python3 -c \"import json; b=json.load(open('docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e2_baseline.json'))['classes']; req={'n_mutants','n_controls','detected','detection_rate','blocking_fp','fp_rate','indeterminate_mutants','indeterminate_controls','meets_threshold'}; assert set(b)=={'1','2','3','4','5'} and all(req<=set(b[k]) for k in b); vs=[json.loads(l)['verdict'] for l in open('docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/runs/e2_verdicts.jsonl')]; assert set(vs)<= {'PASS','BLOCK','INDETERMINATE'}, set(vs); print('BASELINE-OK', len(vs), 'rows')\"`\n- [ ] The AMBIGUOUS/INDETERMINATE counting rule is the pure helper `e2_counting.classify_pair`\n  (INDETERMINATE ⇒ FN on mutants, non-FP on controls; advisory counts for detection, only `block`\n  counts for FP), covered by a golden test with synthetic PASS/BLOCK/INDETERMINATE verdict dicts.\n  Prove: `.venv/bin/python -m pytest tests/unit/experiments/test_e2_counting.py -q`\n- [ ] `README.md` gains an \"E2 — seeded-defect benchmark\" section recording the baseline results,\n  the pre-registered thresholds, how R1/R3/R4/R2 each consume the corpus, the INDETERMINATE\n  run-validity guard, and the degradation ladder. Prove the required sub-sections are present:\n  `grep -q \"E2 — seeded-defect benchmark\" docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/README.md && grep -q \"run-validity\" docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/README.md && grep -Eq \"degrad\" docs/experiments/plan-review-gate/README.md && echo WRITEUP-OK`"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784259780641490001,"uuid":"854e37b0-f0d6-4308-a01d-9de90cb0c971"}